,'2013-06-19 00:00:00','2013-08-13 14:44:44'),(4202,'HelloWorldDispel',2134,2451,'Simple usage of the dispel workflow engine',0,0,0,0,0,0,'2013-06-27 14:18:29','2013-06-27 14:35:12'),(4204,'Importer',2106,2703,'This workflow performs a VisIVO Importer operation extracting meta-data such as the fields histograms.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-07-01 00:00:00','2013-10-10 12:17:42'),(4205,'AutodockVinaFull',2357,2624,'This workflow performs a docking procedure of ligands into a protein. This version allows more advanced user input and is thus suitable for users who have performed docking before. The actual docking process includes splitting of the receptor-file into protein and reference ligand, docking with AutoDock Vina, and export of the dock results. AutoDock Vina creates a grid on the fly and thus no separate grid-building step is performed. For this workflow a protein structure file containing a protein in complex with a reference ligand and a file with the screening library (i.e., ligands that are to be docked into the protein) is required.',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-07-01 14:27:20','2013-09-25 20:25:40'),(4206,'NWChem_convfreq',2355,2624,'This workflow performs the combination of the output geometry with an emtpy (coordinate-free) NWChem-file for frequency calculation (first step: converter) and accomplishes then a frequency calculation with NWChem.',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-07-01 14:42:28','2013-08-19 16:41:05'),(4211,'test_noam_0107',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',0,0,0,0,0,0,'2013-07-02 00:00:00','2013-08-13 14:46:23'),(4212,'test_noam_0107b',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',0,0,0,0,0,0,'2013-07-02 00:00:00','2013-08-13 14:45:13'),(4213,'test_noam_0107_c',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',0,0,0,0,0,0,'2013-07-02 00:00:00','2013-08-13 14:46:07'),(4214,'test_noam_0107d',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',0,0,0,0,0,0,'2013-07-02 00:00:00','2013-08-13 14:45:30'),(4215,'test_noam_0107_gemlca',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',0,0,0,0,0,0,'2013-07-02 00:00:00','2013-08-13 14:45:48'),(4220,'tega0107_test',1402,2103,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,0,0,0,'2013-07-02 00:00:00','2013-08-15 09:52:03'),(4222,'test_noam_0107d_2013-07-02-180000',1403,2402,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',0,0,0,0,0,0,'2013-07-02 00:00:00','2013-07-29 15:23:05'),(4223,'prepareForKeplerWorkflow_01',1403,2402,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',0,0,0,0,0,0,'2013-07-02 00:00:00','2013-07-29 15:22:42'),(4224,'TestWorkflowTaverna2',2134,2451,'Hello anyone test workflow for Taverna2',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-07-03 09:03:20','2013-08-12 11:04:48'),(4226,'NWChem_convfreq_2013-07-03-120435',2355,2402,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-07-03 00:00:00','2013-07-03 11:06:23'),(4239,'DCVLogisticRegression',2354,2902,' This application is an implementation of the repeated double cross validation algorithm, intended for (a) optimizing the complexity of regression models, and (b) for a realistic estimation of prediction errors when the model is applied to new cases (within the population of the data used). In short, in this approach, given a list of x and y variables, we want to find a linear model describing this data as:\n\ny = b0 + b1x1 + ... + bnxn\n\nThe current implementation uses logistic regression in order to find such a model from a given set of x and y variables.',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-07-09 00:00:00','2013-09-02 09:43:30'),(4241,'DCV4Shiwa_2013-07-09-092319',1302,2902,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,1,0,0,0,'2013-07-09 00:00:00','2013-08-12 06:23:39'),(4243,'templatizedworkflow2',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',0,0,0,0,0,0,'2013-07-09 00:00:00','2013-08-13 14:51:46'),(4244,'templatizedworkflow2_2013-07-09-114544',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',0,0,0,0,0,0,'2013-07-09 00:00:00','2013-08-13 14:51:16'),(4250,'DTIpreprocessing3',1302,2902,'The input DTI data are corrected for motion, artefacts and noise. \nDetailed desription: http://www.bioinformaticslaboratory.nl/twiki/bin/view/EBioScience/PredtiUserDoc\nBackground: DTI measures the diffusion of water in and between fibers. The diffusion is high parallel to and low (restricted) perpendicular to the fiber orientation. Per subject, the amount of water diffusion is measured in 30 to 60 three-dimensional (3D) orientations, resulting in a series of 3D volumes. These volumes are encapsulated in a single dataset. These raw data cannot be directly interpreted, but need a complex and computationally demanding analysis. Acquiring a DTI dataset commonly takes 10 minutes. Subjects may have moved during this time. In addition the data may contain artifacts and are hampered by noise. In the preprocessing step, the data are corrected for motion, artefacts and noise. The workflow takes a DTI dataset as input and outputs a volume that is ready for FSL BedpostX processing.',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-07-11 00:00:00','2013-09-02 09:59:30'),(4251,'Freesurfer3',1302,2902,'FreeSurfer is a set of automated tools for reconstruction and exploration of the brains cortical surface from structural MRI data, and overlay of functional MRI data onto the reconstructed surface. \n\nThis freesurfer workflow uses the \"recon-all\" function, which performs all the steps. \nFor more details, please see http://surfer.nmr.mgh.harvard.edu/fswiki/recon-all\n\nWhen using this workflow, please refer to publications in\nhttp://surfer.nmr.mgh.harvard.edu/fswiki/Publications\n\nIMPORTANT: \nFreesurfer has a license, but it is free for academic use. This license is valid only for vlemed VO members. ',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-07-11 00:00:00','2013-09-02 10:08:37'),(4253,'Downsamplesam',1302,2902,'Simulation of low coverage sequence experiments: Randomly samples alignments from a sequence alignment file. It is used to simulate low coverage sequence experiments.',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-07-11 00:00:00','2013-08-15 07:15:41'),(4254,'SNP_annotation-varscan2annovar-annovar',1302,2902,'SNP annotation with Annovar: Adds annotation to variant lists, e.g. gene name, prediction of damage, conservation, known variants',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-07-11 00:00:00','2013-08-15 07:14:19'),(4255,'SNP_calling-pileup-varscan',1302,2902,'SNP calling with samtools and varscan: calls variants from (human) genome re-sequencing data with the programs \'samtools\' and \'varscan\'.\n\nInput: reference genome (fasta format), aligned sequence fragments (bam format), parameters for SNP calling programs\n',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-07-11 00:00:00','2013-08-15 07:15:01'),(4256,'autodock-vina-glite',1302,2902,'todo',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-07-11 00:00:00','2013-08-15 07:20:48'),(4260,'gcAAA',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',0,0,0,1,1,0,'2013-07-15 00:00:00','2013-08-22 13:38:36'),(4354,'GromacsEQ_2013-05-30-215429_2013-07-17-131234',2357,2624,'The equilibration workflow corresponds to the energy minimization but offers the possibilty to equilibrate the protein a little bit further. The minimization is carried out with position constraints on the protein, ensuring its integrety during this step. Afterwards a short constrained MD simulation is performed, allowing the solvent molecules to move freely. As last step a free MD simulation is carried out for a given simulation length. The protocol used for this workflow corresponds to the best practice used in the field. The user only has to provide a plain .pdb file containing a protein.\n',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-08-05 00:00:00','2013-09-25 19:30:07'),(4355,'MD_EM_wParser_2013-07-16-193320_2013-07-17-125416',2357,2624,'The workflow is intended for the new and inexperienced GROMACS user. The user has to provide a plain .pdb file containing the coordinates of a protein. After molecule selection, a force field and water model can be selected, followed by the number of energy minimization steps. Furthermore resource settings can be adjusted. Usally the default settings give reasonable results, producing a solvated and minimized simulation system within a couple of minutes (depending on cluster availability). Such a system can be used for long time simulation with GROMACS or may be processed further with other tools.\nForce field based simulation tools like GROMACS work with so called topologies, describing the interactions within a protein with specific energy functions. Therefore only biomolecules that are described by the available forcefields can be simulated. Pure proteins allways work well, but if you want to simulate some fancy liquid crystals with strangly conjugated PI-systems you may run out of topology parameters.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-08-05 00:00:00','2013-08-12 12:43:14'),(4452,'PS1',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-08-07 00:00:00','2013-08-13 14:48:39'),(4454,'suitetest1a',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-08-07 00:00:00','2013-08-13 14:50:35'),(4502,'ps1b',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-08-07 00:00:00','2013-08-13 14:48:25'),(4551,'PS1cnew',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-08-07 00:00:00','2013-08-13 14:48:09'),(4601,'DTI_Population_Registration',1302,2902,' DTI Population Registration is meant to find spatial correspondence in DTI datasets of all subjects in a certain population. A population contains a group of patients (e.g. depression, schizophrenia, Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis, etc.) and controls. In total, typically 50 subjects are included.\n\nIn this workflow, the mean of all subjects serves as template, towards all subjects are registered. This mean template is iteratively updated until convergence (6 times is optimal). ',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-08-10 07:09:22','2013-08-15 07:19:27'),(4704,'hellobello',2151,1152,'This is my first WF.',0,0,0,1,1,0,'2012-10-04 00:00:00','2013-08-16 12:24:18'),(4705,'AutodockVinaFullcopy',2151,1152,'Abstract Workflow generated by SHIWADesktop',1,1,1,1,1,0,'2013-07-01 00:00:00','2013-08-15 12:35:59'),(4751,'NWChem_convTD',2355,2624,'This workflow performs the combination of the output geometry with an emtpy (coordinate-free) NWChem-file for TD calculation (first step: converter) and accomplishes then a TD calculation with NWChem.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-08-18 00:00:00','2013-10-15 09:21:14'),(4752,'NWChem_convsolv',2355,2624,'This workflow performs the combination of the output geometry with an emtpy (coordinate-free) NWChem-file for a calculation with solvent model (first step: converter) and accomplishes then a solvent-model calculation with NWChem.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-08-18 00:00:00','2013-10-15 09:21:40'),(4753,'NWChem_convMull',2355,2624,'This workflow performs the combination of the output geometry with an emtpy (coordinate-free) NWChem-file for Mulliken calculation (first step: converter) and accomplishes then a Mulliken calculation with NWChem.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-08-18 00:00:00','2013-10-15 09:22:03'),(4802,'DockingWithoutLigandGeneration',2357,2624,'This workflow performs a docking procedure of ligands into a protein. This version allows more advanced user input and is thus suitable for users who have performed docking before. The actual docking process includes splitting of the receptor-file into protein and reference ligand, grid building, docking and rescoring of the dock results. For this workflow a protein structure file containing a protein in complex with a referenceligand and a file with the screening library (i.e., ligands that are to be docked into the protein) is required. The imported screening library will be checked, but no 3D coordinates will be created for the ligands - thus it is the user\'s responsibility to make sure the ligand input is correctly formated (sdf MUST contain all hydrogens of each molecule and all 3 coordinates for each atom)\n',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-08-19 00:00:00','2013-10-10 14:37:04'),(4803,'DockingWithLigandGeneration',2357,2624,'This workflow performs a docking procedure of ligands into a protein. This version is simplified so that only minimal user input is needed and thus is aimed at the novice user. The actual docking process includes splitting of the receptor-file into protein and reference ligand, grid building, docking and rescoring of the dock results. For this workflow a protein structure file containing a protein in complex with a referenceligand and a file with the screening library (ligands) is required.',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-08-19 00:00:00','2013-10-10 14:36:17'),(4805,'DCVLogisticRegression3',2354,2902,' This application is an implementation of the repeated double cross validation algorithm, intended for (a) optimizing the complexity of regression models, and (b) for a realistic estimation of prediction errors when the model is applied to new cases (within the population of the data used). In short, in this approach, given a list of x and y variables, we want to find a linear model describing this data as:\n\ny = b0 + b1x1 + ... + bnxn\n\nThe current implementation uses logistic regression in order to find such a model from a given set of x and y variables.',1,1,1,1,1,0,'2013-08-22 00:00:00','2013-08-22 08:58:57'),(4812,'HFCSynopticMapFromDate',2128,3051,'query the HELIO Feature Catalogue, and retrieves the image with all the features catalgued for certain date.\n\nThis workflow has been downloaded from the myExperiment web site. \nURL: http://www.myexperiment.org/workflows/3293.html',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-08-29 15:00:49','2013-10-11 10:14:20'),(4813,'HFCTable',2128,3204,'WS-PGRADE wrapping workflows for the TAVERNA HFC Sinoptic Table Workflow.\r\n(MyExperiment ID = 3293)\r\n',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-08-29 15:19:47','2013-10-10 13:23:24'),(4852,'erflow-downsamplesam-app-vladimir-concrete',1302,2902,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-08-29 00:00:00','2013-08-29 16:22:30'),(4853,'gcAAAtest3008',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-08-30 00:00:00','2013-08-30 09:25:43'),(4857,'singleTPR_2013-09-02-154649_2013-09-02-144930',2357,2624,'This is a very basic workflow for experienced users, who mainly want to take advantage of the computational resources available through MoSGrid. It is assumed that the user is familiar with GROMACS and that a .tpr containing all information needed for a simulation has been prepared elsewhere. The user has to upload that file and specfiy the resource settings. In general all jobs are queued in the underlying grid system. The smaller the resource requirements are, the faster the job is started. It is strongly recommend to do a pilot run, setting the maximal runtime (corresponds to -maxh option of mdrun, i.e. the computational core of GROMACS) to a couple of minutes, in order to get an idea of the performance.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-02 00:00:00','2013-10-10 15:27:11'),(4858,'BedpostX3',2354,2902,'The FMRIB Software Library (FSL) is a toolbox of programs to analyze brain images. Bedpostx is one of such programs to process DiffusionTensor Imaging (DTI) data acquired with Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI). It reconstructs the fibers in each voxel (called tractograpy) using an advanced method that supports crossing fibers.\nBedpostX stands for Bayesian Estimation of Diffusion Parameters Obtained using Sampling Techniques, where the X stands for modelling crossing fibres. BedpostX runs a Markov Chain Monte Carlo sampling to build up distributions on diffusion parameters at each voxel, creating all the files necessary for running probabilistic tractography. BedpostX allows for modelling crossing fibres within each voxel on the brain and to automatically determine the number of crossing fibres per voxel.\n',1,1,1,1,1,1,'2013-09-03 00:00:00','2013-09-03 08:33:58'),(4859,'SuiteTest1_2013-08-19-150801',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-09-03 00:00:00','2013-09-03 10:33:24'),(4860,'admin',1403,2256,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-08-26 00:00:00','2013-08-26 14:20:25'),(4861,'bwa-akos',1403,2256,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-08-26 00:00:00','2013-08-26 15:05:39'),(4862,'helloDispel',2251,2402,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-09-03 00:00:00','2013-10-08 16:04:40'),(4901,'RemoteMultiImporter2',2106,2703,'This workflow performs a VisIVO Importer operation to import a remote dataset into a VisIVO Binary Table extracting useful meta data such as basic statistics and histograms of the fields or the first rows in a textual file and send an e-mail after the completion.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-05 00:00:00','2013-09-06 09:28:52'),(4902,'MultiImporter2',2106,2703,'This workflow performs a VisIVO Importer operation to import a dataset into a set of Visivo Binary Tables (e.g. in case of GADGET data) extracting useful meta data such as basic statistics and histograms of the fields or the first rows in a textual file.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-06 00:00:00','2013-09-06 09:29:19'),(4903,'RemoteImporter2',2106,2703,'This workflow performs a VisIVO Importer operation to import a remote dataset into a VBT extracting useful meta data such as basic statistics and histograms of the fields or the first rows in a textual file and send an e-mail after the completion.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-06 00:00:00','2013-09-06 09:30:36'),(4904,'Filters2',2106,2703,'This workflow performs a VisIVO Filter operation to a VisIVO Binary Table (VBT) generating a new VBT and relative meta-data.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-06 00:00:00','2013-09-10 10:50:38'),(4905,'SplitFilt2',2106,2703,'This workflow performs a VisIVO Filter split operation to a VisIVO Binary Table generating a set of new VBTs and relative meta-data.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-06 00:00:00','2013-10-10 12:18:16'),(4906,'StatFilter_2013-05-07-125322',2106,2703,'This workflow performs a statistic VisIVO Filter operation to a VisIVO Binary Table (VBT) generating a set of statistics of the VBT fields.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-06 00:00:00','2013-09-06 10:39:17'),(4913,'NWChem_TSsearch_2013-09-11-161349',2355,2624,'This workflow allows the transition state (TS) search of a given set of molecules using NWChem.',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-09-11 00:00:00','2013-09-11 15:11:05'),(4952,'WriteVO_2013-09-04-121829',1403,2256,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-09-04 00:00:00','2013-09-04 10:55:08'),(4955,'AEGIS_CMPC_SG-SPEEDUP_Workflow',2851,3101,'Workflow behind AEGIS CMPC SG - (Q)SPEEDUP portlet. It has three components:\n\n - (Q)SPEEDUP-PREPARATION retrieves physical system configuration from the database. This JSON output is then converted to the application specific configuration file, and forwarded to the next process in the workflow. This is not CPU-intensive task, and it is executed at the server that hosts gUSE/WS-PGRADE portal (localhost).\n\n - (Q)SPEEDUP-EXECUTION is responsible for the application execution at DCI and the retrieval of the results.\n\n - (Q)SPEEDUP-PUBLICATION transforms results of the application to the JSON format, and stores the result in the database through the RESTful web service. \n',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-13 09:29:05','2013-09-13 09:30:52'),(4956,'AEGIS_CMPC_SG-GPSCL_Workflow',2851,3101,'AEGIS CMPC SG GP-SCL portlet relies on the  AEGIS_CMPC_SG-GPSCL_Workflow. The workflow has the following components:\r\n\r\n - GP-SCL-PREPARATION retrieves physical system configuration from the database, and produces application-specific parameter input file. The task is executed on the server hosting gUSE/WS-PGRADE portal.\r\n\r\n - GP-SCL-EXECUTION performs submission of the simulation to DCI, and output retrieval. After the execution, produced results are divided between two tasks running in parallel: GP-SCL-GRAPH and GP-SCL-ANIMATION.\r\n\r\n - GP-SCL-GRAPH produces graphs requested in the configuration. Graphs are produced using gnuplot-based scripts. This task is not CPU-intensive, and therefore is performed on the local machine.\r\n\r\n - GP-SCL-ANIMATION produces animation (movie) of a dilute trapped Bose-Einstein condensate evolution in time. This part of the workflow is CPU intensive and is executed on the DCI.\r\n\r\n - GP-SCL-PUBLICATION accumulates results, graphs, and locations of the movies, and stores them into the document-oriented database.\r\n',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-13 09:38:24','2013-09-13 09:38:36'),(4957,'AMBER_2013-09-14-001705',2802,3153,'AMBER (an acronym for Assisted Model Building with Energy Refinement) is a family of force fields for molecular dynamics of biomolecules originally developed by the late Peter Kollman\'s group at the University of California, San Francisco. AMBER is also the name for the molecular dynamics software package that simulates these force fields. ',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-13 00:00:00','2013-10-15 14:59:23'),(4958,'BLAST_2013-09-17-104753',2802,3152,'BLAST is one of the most widely used bioinformatics programs that finds regions of local similarity between sequences. ',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-17 00:00:00','2013-10-15 15:01:01'),(4959,'testwf',1252,1152,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-09-17 00:00:00','2013-09-17 12:41:13'),(4961,'VisIVODynMov',2106,2703,'This workflow employs VisIVO Tools to import cosmological datasets and builds customized 3D visualization and movies from such datasets. A cosmological simulation produces a set of snapshots at different time steps with different time tags, not linearly distributed. The researcher is normally interested in sub-regions, voids or halos.\nThis application produces a 3D movie representing the evolution of a cosmological N-body simulation into the defined sub-region.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-18 00:00:00','2013-09-18 16:16:02'),(4963,'shiwaUploadTestBela',1404,3102,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-09-19 00:00:00','2013-09-19 10:31:01'),(4965,'WriteVO_2013-09-19-120136',1403,2256,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-09-19 00:00:00','2013-09-19 12:02:47'),(4966,'DynMovie',2106,2703,'This workflow employs VisIVO Tools to generate a dynamic movie interpolating several steps of a time evolution of a cosmological dataset (in VisIVO Binary Table format).',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-20 00:00:00','2013-09-20 15:07:15'),(4967,'WriteVO',2106,2703,'This workflow employs VisIVO Filter to write a VO Table corresponding to a VisIVO Binary Table.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-20 00:00:00','2013-09-20 15:17:27'),(4968,'createMovie',2106,2703,'This workflow employs VisIVO Tools to generate a camera path corresponding to a user defined path and generates the corresponding final movie.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-20 00:00:00','2013-09-20 15:08:48'),(4969,'FASTDNAML_2013-09-23-040604',2802,3152,'FastDNAml is a construction of phylogenetic trees of DNA sequences application using maximum likelihood.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-23 00:00:00','2013-10-15 15:02:10'),(4970,'MUSCLE_2013-09-23-040835',2802,3152,'MUSCLE is a program for creating multiple alignments of amino acid or nucleotide sequences. A range of options is provided that give you the choice of optimizing accuracy, speed, or some compromise between the two.Default parameters are those that give the best average accuracy in our tests. ',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-23 00:00:00','2013-10-15 15:03:02'),(4971,'PHASE_2013-09-23-040757',2802,3152,'PHASE a Software Package for Phylogenetics And Sequence Evolution. Though this software package can handle various types of molecular sequences, it is designed specifically for use with RNA sequences that have a conserved secondary structure, e.g., rRNAs and tRNAs. ',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-23 00:00:00','2013-10-15 15:03:28'),(4972,'BLENDER_2013-09-17-170226',2802,3154,'Blender is a free and open-source 3D computer graphics software product used for creating animated films, visual effects, art, 3D printed models, interactive 3D applications and video games. Blender\'s features include 3D modeling, UV unwrapping, texturing, rigging and skinning, fluid and smoke simulation, particle simulation, soft body simulation, animating, match moving, camera tracking, rendering, video editing and compositing. ',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-23 00:00:00','2013-10-15 15:10:32'),(4974,'two_job_test',1252,1152,'This a two job test workflow.\nThe workflow is configured for GT4 - although while the GT4 resources currently configured as the ngs.wmin.ac.uk, you may need to specify GT4 resources which your portal is configured to submit to.\n\nThe executables are shell files, and so the resources may be configured to submit to any resource your ws-pgrade portal is configured to submit to.\n\nIf the workflow is working correctly, the OUTPUT file of Job1 should contain five lines:\n\"\ntest file\n\nargs: -t job 0\n\nargs: -t job 1\n\"\nGathering the command line arguments of Job0 and job1\n\n\n',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-24 00:00:00','2013-10-15 09:40:12'),(4975,'Comcapt',2358,2402,'Capture of comets from the interstellar space by the Galactic tide',1,0,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-24 00:00:00','2013-10-14 07:19:29'),(4977,'Mestream',2358,2402,'Modelling the dynamical Evolution of meteoroid stream',1,0,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-24 00:00:00','2013-10-14 07:22:59'),(4978,'Planck',2358,2402,'Simulations of the ESA Planck satellite mission\n',1,0,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-24 00:00:00','2013-10-14 07:17:42'),(4979,'Franec',2358,2402,'Frascati Raphson Newton Evolutionary Code) / BaSTI (Bag of Stellar Tracks and Isochrones)',1,0,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-24 00:00:00','2013-10-14 07:23:49'),(4980,'ModGravity5',2106,2703,'This workflow employs VisIVO tools to performe a customized visualization for aiding the analysis of modified gravity simulations, more specifically inspecting datasets to discover anomalies by comparing appropriately with datasets coming from standard gravity models (including dark energy).',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-24 00:00:00','2013-09-24 15:16:21'),(4981,'get_geog_cro-ngi',2903,2705,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-09-25 00:00:00','2013-09-25 10:29:59'),(4982,'clone-tega1_2013-09-25-133622',1402,2103,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-09-25 00:00:00','2013-09-25 12:37:41'),(5001,'wrf_cro-ngi',2903,2705,'WPS+WRF workflow for CRO-NGI grid infrastructure (GT5)',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-09-30 00:00:00','2013-10-10 11:38:55'),(5002,'metaWorkflow_Test',2302,2452,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-09-30 00:00:00','2013-09-30 14:08:12'),(5003,'Taverna2_Test_2013-09-30-160414',2302,2452,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-09-30 00:00:00','2013-09-30 15:16:34'),(5004,'metaWorkflow_Test_2013-09-30-160349',2302,2452,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-09-30 00:00:00','2013-09-30 15:16:58'),(5005,'prepareForKepler_Test_2013-09-30-160402',2302,2452,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-09-30 00:00:00','2013-09-30 15:17:23'),(5006,'OPENFOAM_2013-10-01-102936',2802,2705,'OpenFOAM is a free, open source CFD software package developed by OpenCFD Ltd at ESI Group and distributed by the OpenFOAM Foundation . It has a large user base across most areas of engineering and science, from both commercial and academic organisations. OpenFOAM has an extensive range of features to solve anything from complex fluid flows involving chemical reactions, turbulence and heat transfer, to solid dynamics and electromagnetics. ',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-10-01 00:00:00','2013-10-13 02:50:13'),(5007,'NWCHEM_2013-10-01-102957',2802,3153,'NWChem is an ab initio computational chemistry software package which also includes quantum chemical and molecular dynamics functionality.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-10-01 00:00:00','2013-10-15 15:00:00'),(5009,'GROMACS_2013-10-01-104808',2802,3153,'GROMACS (GROningen MAchine for Chemical Simulations) is a molecular dynamics Simulation package. \ni.e. simulate the Newtonian equations of motion for systems with hundreds to millions of particles.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-10-01 00:00:00','2013-10-15 15:00:30'),(5010,'CLUSTALW_2013-10-01-105410',2802,3152,'CLUSTALW-MPI is ClustalW Analysis Using Grid and Parallel Computing based on clustalW, the multiple sequence alignment program. This application can run in parallel on a cluster of Linux machines using MPI.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-10-01 00:00:00','2013-10-15 15:03:56'),(5011,'wrf_complete',2903,2705,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-10-01 00:00:00','2013-10-01 13:50:00'),(5051,'tega_0310_test_2013-10-03-080106',1402,2103,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-10-03 00:00:00','2013-10-03 08:29:19'),(5058,'SSF5',2951,3151,'Statistical Seismology Function 5 (SSF5): Ground motion prediction equations (GMPEs).\nThis workflow evaluates the behavior of a chosen GMPE, i.e. attenuation model, and enables the users to examine the effect of using that specific GMPE in the PSHA studies.\nIt is possible to evaluate the chosen model for different output types it supports and also for different input parameters.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-10-06 00:00:00','2013-10-06 23:36:00'),(5059,'SSF7',2951,3151,'Statistical Seismology Function 7 (SSF7): Statistical calculations for seismic risk.\nThis workflow performs seismic risk calculations depending on the PSHA results obtained by using SSF4 or SSF6 workflows.\nExpected annual damage ratios (EADRs) are calculated for a given arbitrary number of different structure types provided together with corresponding damage probability matrices (DPMs).',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-10-06 00:00:00','2013-10-06 23:42:17'),(5060,'SSSG-AU',2951,3151,'SSS-Gateway Advanced Use workflow.\nThis workflow provides a wrapper job for executing user programs, written in different programming languages, which involve many calls to Statistical Seismology Functions (SSFs) arbitrarily. \nRemote API calls are performed for executing SSFs requested by user programs, hence Remote Access should be enabled in the WS-PGRADE gateway for using this workflow.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-10-06 00:00:00','2013-10-06 23:46:46'),(5061,'SSF1',2951,3151,'Statistical Seismology Function 1 (SSF1): Integration of multi-source data for increased reliability and quality.\nThis workflow combines different earthquake catalogs to obtain a more reliable integrated earthquake catalog and also analyzes the produced catalog for completeness.\nIt allows an arbitrary number of earthquake catalogs to be used as input and also provides the option to download catalogs from a number of predefined sources.\nIt is possible to specify different parameters for combining (such as location bounds, date range, etc.) and for producing completeness results.\n',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-10-06 00:00:00','2013-10-06 23:04:26'),(5062,'SSF2',2951,3151,'Statistical Seismology Function 2 (SSF2): Determination of probability distributions and their input parameters.\nThis workflow estimates input parameters of Richter\'s magnitude-frequency relation for different probabilistic seismic hazard analysis (PSHA) models and additionally estimates parameters of different renewal models used in PSHA studies, using a chosen estimation technique among the provided ones.\nThe estimation process uses a given earthquake catalog and a given set of seismic sources. Parameter estimates are computed, using the provided earthquake catalog, for each seismic source provided as an input.\n',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-10-06 00:00:00','2013-10-06 23:23:09'),(5063,'SSF3',2951,3151,'Statistical Seismology Function 3 (SSF3): Robust techniques for the parameter estimation in models and relations.\nThis workflow estimates input parameters of Richter\'s magnitude-frequency relation for different probabilistic seismic hazard analysis (PSHA) models and additionally estimates parameters of different renewal models used in PSHA studies, using a robust estimation technique.\nThe estimation process uses a given earthquake catalog and a given set of seismic sources. Parameter estimates are computed, using the provided earthquake catalog, for each seismic source provided as an input.\nFurthermore, it is possible to choose the error distribution and related parameters, which are to be used in the estimation process. ',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-10-06 00:00:00','2013-10-06 23:26:51'),(5064,'SSF4',2951,3151,'Statistical Seismology Function 4 (SSF4): Complex predictive modeling of earthquake phenomena in time-space domains.\nThis workflow performs probabilistic seismic hazard analysis (PSHA) computations for a specified site region of interest.\nA given set of seismic sources, for which analysis parameters are estimated beforehand (most probably using SSF2 or SSF3 workflows), is used in PSHA calculations. \nIt is possible to choose among different PSHA, renewal, magnitude and attenuation models. In addition, various parameters for the analysis computations can be specified before execution.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-10-06 00:00:00','2013-10-06 23:31:39'),(5065,'SSF6',2951,3151,'Statistical Seismology Function 6 (SSF6): Complex logic-tree and sensitivity analysis in probabilistic seismic hazard assessment.\nThis workflow performs logic-tree based probabilistic seismic hazard analysis (PSHA) computations for a specified site region of interest.\nA given set of seismic sources, for which analysis parameters are estimated beforehand (most probably using SSF2 or SSF3 workflows), is used in PSHA calculations. \nIt is possible to select multiple different PSHA, magnitude and attenuation models for the same analysis study. For each selected model a subjective probability, which will be used in logic-tree calculations, is assigned. In addition, various parameters for the analysis computations can be specified before execution.',1,1,0,1,1,1,'2013-10-06 00:00:00','2013-10-06 23:39:45'),(5066,'Str_test',2251,3201,'This is the description of the abstractWorkflow',1,1,0,1,1,0,'2013-10-08 00:00:00','2013-10-08 13:52:34'),(5067,'FindFlaresData',2128